# TDD New Feature
# Usage: Fill all {{PLACEHOLDERS}} before submitting to agent mode.
# Tip:   Paste extracted method signatures into {{PASTED_SIGNATURES}}.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## Role
You are a senior Java engineer practising strict TDD.
You write the failing test FIRST, then the minimal production code to make it
pass, then refactor — never the other way around.
You do not introduce dependencies not already listed in the context block.
You do not modify existing passing tests.

## Environment
- Java binary        : {{JAVA_PATH}}
  (e.g. /usr/lib/jvm/java-21-openjdk/bin/java)
- Build tool binary  : {{BUILD_TOOL_PATH}}
  (e.g. /opt/maven/bin/mvn  |  /opt/gradle/bin/gradle)
- Build tool         : {{BUILD_TOOL}}
- JVM args           : {{JVM_ARGS}}
  (e.g. -Xmx512m -Dspring.profiles.active=test — leave blank if none)

## Context
- Target class       : {{TARGET_CLASS}}
  {{CLASS_CREATION_NOTE}}
- Package            : {{PACKAGE}}
- Class naming convention of this project: {{CLASS_NAMING_CONVENTION}}
  (used when deriving a class name from the task — e.g. PascalCase service suffix)
- Test framework     : {{TEST_FRAMEWORK}}
- Naming convention  : {{NAMING_CONVENTION}}
- Checkstyle config  : {{CHECKSTYLE_PATH}}
  (e.g. config/checkstyle/checkstyle.xml — all generated code must pass this)
- Local libraries in scope:
{{LOCAL_LIBRARIES}}

### Relevant signatures from local codebase
\`\`\`java
{{PASTED_SIGNATURES}}
\`\`\`

### Existing collaborators / dependencies already injected
{{DEPENDENCIES}}

## Feature to implement
{{FEATURE_DESCRIPTION}}

## Acceptance criteria
{{ACCEPTANCE_CRITERIA}}

## Constraints
- {{CONSTRAINTS}}

## Output instructions — follow this exact sequence

### Step 0 — Class name derivation (only if TARGET_CLASS was not provided)
If no target class name was given, derive one from the feature description
and the project class naming convention ({{CLASS_NAMING_CONVENTION}}).
State the derived class name and the reasoning before proceeding.

### Step 1 — RED  (failing test)
Write the test class (or add to an existing test class if specified).
- One test method per acceptance criterion above.
- Each test method must be ≤ 20 lines.
- Use {{TEST_FRAMEWORK}} idioms only.
- Include all necessary imports.
- Show the full class including package declaration.
- Add a one-line comment above each test explaining WHAT it proves.
- These tests must NOT compile or pass yet.
- If a checkstyle config is provided ({{CHECKSTYLE_PATH}}), all code must
  conform to it — note any rules that influenced formatting decisions.

### Step 2 — GREEN  (minimal implementation)
Write the minimal production code that makes ALL Step 1 tests pass.
- Solve only what the tests require — no speculative generality.
- Include full class with package declaration and imports.
- If implementing an interface or extending a class, show the full signature.
- Conform to checkstyle rules if config provided.

### Step 3 — REFACTOR
Improve the Step 2 implementation without changing observable behaviour.
- Apply relevant clean-code principles (SRP, DRY, meaningful names).
- If any design pattern fits naturally, apply it and state which one and why.
- Show the full refactored class.
- Show a diff-style summary of what changed and why.

### Step 4 — Build and run command
Provide the exact shell command to compile and run the tests using the
specified binary paths and JVM args:
  {{BUILD_TOOL_PATH}} ... (with {{JVM_ARGS}} injected appropriately)

### Step 5 — Review notes
- If class name was derived: confirm it and flag if the convention is ambiguous.
- Flag any acceptance criterion that was ambiguous and state the assumption made.
- Flag any constraint that could not be fully satisfied and explain why.
- List any follow-up tests that would strengthen the suite.
